-- Step 1: Insert chapter metadata
INSERT INTO chapters (book_id, chapter_number, overview, theme, key_word_original, key_word_meaning, outline)
SELECT b.id, 11,
  'John 11 records the climactic sign in the Book of Signs: the raising of Lazarus from the dead. This miracle is the seventh and greatest of Jesus'' signs in John, and it precipitates the decision to put him to death — the very act that will accomplish the resurrection he has just demonstrated. The chapter opens with the illness of Lazarus of Bethany, brother of Mary and Martha (vv.1-3). Upon hearing the news, Jesus deliberately delays two days (v.6), declaring, ''This sickness is not unto death, but for the glory of God, that the Son of God might be glorified thereby'' (v.4). He tells the disciples plainly, ''Lazarus is dead. And I am glad for your sakes that I was not there, to the intent ye may believe'' (vv.14-15). Thomas responds with grim loyalty: ''Let us also go, that we may die with him'' (v.16). Upon arrival, Jesus finds Lazarus has been in the tomb four days (v.17). Martha meets him first and confesses, ''Lord, if thou hadst been here, my brother had not died. But I know, that even now, whatsoever thou wilt ask of God, God will give it thee'' (vv.21-22). Jesus declares: ''I am the resurrection, and the life: he that believeth in me, though he were dead, yet shall he live: And whosoever liveth and believeth in me shall never die'' (vv.25-26) — the fifth great ''I AM'' statement in John. Martha responds with the model confession: ''Yea, Lord: I believe that thou art the Christ, the Son of God, which should come into the world'' (v.27). Mary comes weeping to Jesus, the Jews follow weeping, and then: ''Jesus wept'' (v.35) — the shortest verse in the Bible, yet one of the most profound, revealing the full humanity and compassion of the incarnate Son. At the tomb, Jesus commands the stone removed. Martha protests — ''Lord, by this time he stinketh: for he hath been dead four days'' (v.39). Jesus prays publicly to the Father, then cries with a loud voice, ''Lazarus, come forth'' (v.43). The dead man emerges, bound in grave clothes, and Jesus says, ''Loose him, and let him go'' (v.44). Many believe, but some report to the Pharisees. The Sanhedrin convenes and Caiaphas prophesies unwittingly: ''It is expedient for us, that one man should die for the people, and that the whole nation perish not'' (v.50). John notes that Caiaphas spoke not of himself but prophesied that Jesus would die ''for that nation; and not for that nation only, but that also he should gather together in one the children of God that were scattered abroad'' (vv.51-52). From that day they plot to kill him (v.53).',
  'The Resurrection and the Life — Death Conquered, Death Decreed',
  'ἀνάστασις (anastasis)',
  'Resurrection, rising up, standing again — from ana (up, again) + histēmi (to stand). In John 11, Jesus declares himself to be the anastasis: not merely one who performs resurrection but one who IS the resurrection (v.25). This is the definitive claim: life and resurrection are not events Jesus causes externally but realities he embodies personally. ''He that believeth in me, though he were dead, yet shall he live'' (v.25). The raising of Lazarus demonstrates this claim visibly — the dead man rises because the Resurrection himself stands at the tomb and commands it. The irony of the chapter is that this demonstration of resurrection power leads directly to the decree of Jesus'' own death (v.53), which will itself lead to the ultimate resurrection (ch.20).',
  '["The Sickness of Lazarus (vv.1-6): Now a certain man was sick named Lazarus of Bethany the town of Mary and her sister Martha. It was that Mary which anointed the Lord with ointment and wiped his feet with her hair whose brother Lazarus was sick. Therefore his sisters sent unto him saying Lord behold he whom thou lovest is sick. When Jesus heard that he said This sickness is not unto death but for the glory of God that the Son of God might be glorified thereby. Now Jesus loved Martha and her sister and Lazarus. When he had heard therefore that he was sick he abode two days still in the same place where he was","Jesus Goes to Judaea (vv.7-16): Then after that saith he to his disciples Let us go into Judaea again. His disciples say unto him Master the Jews of late sought to stone thee and goest thou thither again? Jesus answered Are there not twelve hours in the day? If any man walk in the day he stumbleth not because he seeth the light of this world. But if a man walk in the night he stumbleth because there is no light in him. These things said he and after that he saith unto them Our friend Lazarus sleepeth but I go that I may awake him out of sleep. Then said his disciples Lord if he sleep he shall do well. Howbeit Jesus spake of his death but they thought that he had spoken of taking of rest in sleep. Then said Jesus unto them plainly Lazarus is dead. And I am glad for your sakes that I was not there to the intent ye may believe. Nevertheless let us go unto him. Then said Thomas which is called Didymus unto his fellowdisciples Let us also go that we may die with him","I Am the Resurrection and the Life (vv.17-27): Then when Jesus came he found that he had lain in the grave four days already. Now Bethany was nigh unto Jerusalem about fifteen furlongs off. And many of the Jews came to Martha and Mary to comfort them concerning their brother. Then Martha as soon as she heard that Jesus was coming went and met him but Mary sat still in the house. Then said Martha unto Jesus Lord if thou hadst been here my brother had not died. But I know that even now whatsoever thou wilt ask of God God will give it thee. Jesus saith unto her Thy brother shall rise again. Martha saith unto him I know that he shall rise again in the resurrection at the last day. Jesus said unto her I am the resurrection and the life he that believeth in me though he were dead yet shall he live. And whosoever liveth and believeth in me shall never die. Believest thou this? She saith unto him Yea Lord I believe that thou art the Christ the Son of God which should come into the world","Jesus Weeps (vv.28-37): And when she had so said she went her way and called Mary her sister secretly saying The Master is come and calleth for thee. As soon as she heard that she arose quickly and came unto him. Now Jesus was not yet come into the town but was in that place where Martha met him. The Jews then which were with her in the house and comforted her when they saw Mary that she rose up hastily and went out followed her saying She goeth unto the grave to weep there. Then when Mary was come where Jesus was and saw him she fell down at his feet saying unto him Lord if thou hadst been here my brother had not died. When Jesus therefore saw her weeping and the Jews also weeping which came with her he groaned in the spirit and was troubled. And said Where have ye laid him? They said unto him Lord come and see. Jesus wept. Then said the Jews Behold how he loved him! And some of them said Could not this man which opened the eyes of the blind have caused that even this man should not have died?","Lazarus Come Forth (vv.38-44): Jesus therefore again groaning in himself cometh to the grave. It was a cave and a stone lay upon it. Jesus said Take ye away the stone. Martha the sister of him that was dead saith unto him Lord by this time he stinketh for he hath been dead four days. Jesus saith unto her Said I not unto thee that if thou wouldest believe thou shouldest see the glory of God? Then they took away the stone from the place where the dead was laid. And Jesus lifted up his eyes and said Father I thank thee that thou hast heard me. And I knew that thou hearest me always but because of the people which stand by I said it that they may believe that thou hast sent me. And when he thus had spoken he cried with a loud voice Lazarus come forth. And he that was dead came forth bound hand and foot with graveclothes and his face was bound about with a napkin. Jesus saith unto them Loose him and let him go","The Plot to Kill Jesus (vv.45-57): Then many of the Jews which came to Mary and had seen the things which Jesus did believed on him. But some of them went their ways to the Pharisees and told them what things Jesus had done. Then gathered the chief priests and the Pharisees a council and said What do we? For this man doeth many miracles. If we let him thus alone all men will believe on him and the Romans shall come and take away both our place and nation. And one of them named Caiaphas being the high priest that same year said unto them Ye know nothing at all nor consider that it is expedient for us that one man should die for the people and that the whole nation perish not. And this spake he not of himself but being high priest that year he prophesied that Jesus should die for that nation and not for that nation only but that also he should gather together in one the children of God that were scattered abroad. Then from that day forth they took counsel together for to put him to death. Jesus therefore walked no more openly among the Jews but went thence unto a country near to the wilderness into a city called Ephraim and there continued with his disciples. And the Jews'' passover was nigh at hand and many went out of the country up to Jerusalem before the passover to purify themselves. Then sought they for Jesus and spake among themselves as they stood in the temple What think ye that he will not come to the feast? Now both the chief priests and the Pharisees had given a commandment that if any man knew where he were he should shew it that they might take him"]'
FROM books b WHERE b.name = 'John';

-- Step 2: Insert all 57 verses
INSERT INTO verses (chapter_id, verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
SELECT c.id, v.verse_number, v.kjv_text, v.original_text, v.transliteration, v.study_note, v.doctrinal_note
FROM chapters c
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1, 'Now a certain man was sick, named Lazarus, of Bethany, the town of Mary and her sister Martha.',
   'ἦν δέ τις ἀσθενῶν Λάζαρος ἀπὸ Βηθανίας ἐκ τῆς κώμης Μαρίας καὶ Μάρθας τῆς ἀδελφῆς αὐτῆς',
   'ēn de tis asthenōn Lazaros apo Bēthanias ek tēs kōmēs Marias kai Marthas tēs adelphēs autēs',
   '''Lazarus'' (Lazaros — Greek form of the Hebrew El''azar, meaning ''God has helped''). The name is theologically fitting: God will indeed help, but in a way far beyond human expectation. ''Bethany'' (Bēthania — ''House of Affliction'' or ''House of Dates''), about two miles east of Jerusalem on the Mount of Olives (v.18). John identifies the town by its association with Mary and Martha, assuming his readers know them. This Lazarus is distinct from the beggar in Luke 16:19-31.',
   NULL),
  (2, 'It was that Mary which anointed the Lord with ointment, and wiped his feet with her hair, whose brother Lazarus was sick.',
   'ἦν δὲ Μαριὰμ ἡ ἀλείψασα τὸν κύριον μύρῳ καὶ ἐκμάξασα τοὺς πόδας αὐτοῦ ταῖς θριξὶν αὐτῆς ἧς ὁ ἀδελφὸς Λάζαρος ἠσθένει',
   'ēn de Mariam hē aleipsasa ton kyrion myrō kai ekmaxasa tous podas autou tais thrixin autēs hēs ho adelphos Lazaros ēsthenei',
   'John identifies Mary by an event he has not yet narrated (the anointing occurs in 12:1-8), suggesting his readers already know the story from oral tradition or the Synoptic Gospels (cf. Mark 14:3-9). ''Anointed the Lord with ointment'' (aleipsasa ton kyrion myrō) — the use of ''Lord'' (kyrios) here is significant: Mary anointed the one she recognised as Lord. The anticipatory reference creates narrative tension: the one whose sister anoints Jesus for burial is about to die and be raised.',
   NULL),
  (3, 'Therefore his sisters sent unto him, saying, Lord, behold, he whom thou lovest is sick.',
   'ἀπέστειλαν οὖν αἱ ἀδελφαὶ πρὸς αὐτὸν λέγουσαι Κύριε ἴδε ὃν φιλεῖς ἀσθενεῖ',
   'apesteilan oun hai adelphai pros auton legousai Kyrie ide hon phileis asthenei',
   '''He whom thou lovest'' (hon phileis — the one you love with affection, phileō). The sisters do not ask for healing; they simply inform Jesus and trust his love. This is a model prayer: stating the need before the Lord without dictating the response. ''Is sick'' (asthenei — is weak, ill) — the same root as asthenōn in v.1. The message conveys both urgency and trust: surely the one who loves Lazarus will come.',
   NULL),
  (4, 'When Jesus heard that, he said, This sickness is not unto death, but for the glory of God, that the Son of God might be glorified thereby.',
   'ἀκούσας δὲ ὁ Ἰησοῦς εἶπεν Αὕτη ἡ ἀσθένεια οὐκ ἔστιν πρὸς θάνατον ἀλλ᾽ ὑπὲρ τῆς δόξης τοῦ θεοῦ ἵνα δοξασθῇ ὁ υἱὸς τοῦ θεοῦ δι᾽ αὐτῆς',
   'akousas de ho Iēsous eipen Hautē hē astheneia ouk estin pros thanaton all hyper tēs doxēs tou theou hina doxasthē ho huios tou theou di autēs',
   '''Not unto death'' (ouk estin pros thanaton — not directed toward death as its final outcome). Lazarus will die, but death will not have the last word. ''For the glory of God'' (hyper tēs doxēs tou theou — on behalf of God''s glory). The purpose of suffering here is explicitly theological: it serves the manifestation of divine glory through the Son. ''That the Son of God might be glorified'' — the raising of Lazarus glorifies both Father and Son, revealing Jesus'' sovereign power over death.',
   'This verse establishes a principle that applies beyond Lazarus: suffering and even death can serve the glory of God. The sickness was real, the death was real, but neither was the final word. God''s glory is revealed not in the prevention of suffering but in the demonstration of power through and beyond suffering. This is the pattern of the cross itself.'),
  (5, 'Now Jesus loved Martha, and her sister, and Lazarus.',
   'ἠγάπα δὲ ὁ Ἰησοῦς τὴν Μάρθαν καὶ τὴν ἀδελφὴν αὐτῆς καὶ τὸν Λάζαρον',
   'ēgapa de ho Iēsous tēn Marthan kai tēn adelphēn autēs kai ton Lazaron',
   'John uses agapaō (ēgapa — he loved) here, the verb of deliberate, self-giving love, while the sisters used phileō (v.3, personal affection). John alternates these verbs throughout the Gospel (cf. 21:15-17). The statement is placed strategically before the delay in v.6: Jesus loved them — therefore he waited. The delay was not indifference but sovereign love acting according to a higher purpose. Martha is named first, consistent with her role as the elder sister and household manager (cf. Luke 10:38-42).',
   NULL),
  (6, 'When he had heard therefore that he was sick, he abode two days still in the same place where he was.',
   'ὡς οὖν ἤκουσεν ὅτι ἀσθενεῖ τότε μὲν ἔμεινεν ἐν ᾧ ἦν τόπῳ δύο ἡμέρας',
   'hōs oun ēkousen hoti asthenei tote men emeinen en hō ēn topō dyo hēmeras',
   '''He abode two days still'' (emeinen... dyo hēmeras — he remained two days). The ''therefore'' (oun) is startling: because he loved them, he stayed. Jesus'' delay ensured Lazarus would be dead four days by the time he arrived (v.17), removing any possibility of claiming a premature burial or a resuscitation of someone not truly dead. Rabbinic tradition held that the soul lingered near the body for three days hoping to re-enter; after four days, death was considered irreversible. Jesus waited to make the miracle undeniable.',
   NULL),
  (7, 'Then after that saith he to his disciples, Let us go into Judaea again.',
   'ἔπειτα μετὰ τοῦτο λέγει τοῖς μαθηταῖς Ἄγωμεν εἰς τὴν Ἰουδαίαν πάλιν',
   'epeita meta touto legei tois mathētais Agōmen eis tēn Ioudaian palin',
   '''Let us go into Judaea again'' (agōmen eis tēn Ioudaian palin — the subjunctive agōmen means ''let us go together''). ''Again'' (palin) recalls the danger: Jesus had withdrawn from Judaea because of threats (10:39-40). Now he deliberately returns, knowing the danger. The disciples are alarmed (v.8). Jesus walks toward death — not his friend''s, but his own — for the raising of Lazarus will set in motion the events leading to Calvary (vv.47-53).',
   NULL),
  (8, 'His disciples say unto him, Master, the Jews of late sought to stone thee; and goest thou thither again?',
   'λέγουσιν αὐτῷ οἱ μαθηταί Ῥαββί νῦν ἐζήτουν σε λιθάσαι οἱ Ἰουδαῖοι καὶ πάλιν ὑπάγεις ἐκεῖ',
   'legousin autō hoi mathētai Rhabbi nyn ezētoun se lithasai hoi Ioudaioi kai palin hypageis ekei',
   '''Master'' (Rhabbi — Rabbi, Teacher). ''Of late sought to stone thee'' (nyn ezētoun se lithasai — just recently they were seeking to stone you, referring to 10:31-33). The disciples'' fear is reasonable: the last visit to Jerusalem nearly ended in death. ''Goest thou thither again?'' expresses incredulity. The disciples think in terms of self-preservation; Jesus thinks in terms of the Father''s will and the appointed ''hour.''',
   NULL),
  (9, 'Jesus answered, Are there not twelve hours in the day? If any man walk in the day, he stumbleth not, because he seeth the light of this world.',
   'ἀπεκρίθη Ἰησοῦς Οὐχὶ δώδεκα ὧραί εἰσιν τῆς ἡμέρας ἐάν τις περιπατῇ ἐν τῇ ἡμέρᾳ οὐ προσκόπτει ὅτι τὸ φῶς τοῦ κόσμου τούτου βλέπει',
   'apekrithē Iēsous Ouchi dōdeka hōrai eisin tēs hēmeras ean tis peripatē en tē hēmera ou proskoptei hoti to phōs tou kosmou toutou blepei',
   '''Twelve hours in the day'' — Jesus uses the fixed daylight hours as a metaphor for his divinely appointed time of ministry. As long as he walks within the Father''s will (''the day''), he cannot be harmed prematurely. ''He stumbleth not'' (ou proskoptei — does not stumble, trip, or fall). The ''light of this world'' here refers to the natural sun, but the double meaning is unmistakable: Jesus himself is the light of the world (8:12; 9:5). Walking in his light means walking safely within God''s plan.',
   NULL),
  (10, 'But if a man walk in the night, he stumbleth, because there is no light in him.',
   'ἐὰν δέ τις περιπατῇ ἐν τῇ νυκτί προσκόπτει ὅτι τὸ φῶς οὐκ ἔστιν ἐν αὐτῷ',
   'ean de tis peripatē en tē nykti proskoptei hoti to phōs ouk estin en autō',
   '''In the night'' (en tē nykti) — walking outside God''s will, acting in spiritual darkness. ''There is no light in him'' (to phōs ouk estin en autō — the light is not in him). John''s Gospel contrasts light and darkness throughout (1:5; 3:19-21; 8:12; 12:35-36). Judas will go out ''and it was night'' (13:30). The one who acts apart from God''s timing and purposes stumbles because he lacks internal illumination — the guidance that comes from walking with God.',
   NULL),
  (11, 'These things said he: and after that he saith unto them, Our friend Lazarus sleepeth; but I go, that I may awake him out of sleep.',
   'ταῦτα εἶπεν καὶ μετὰ τοῦτο λέγει αὐτοῖς Λάζαρος ὁ φίλος ἡμῶν κεκοίμηται ἀλλὰ πορεύομαι ἵνα ἐξυπνίσω αὐτόν',
   'tauta eipen kai meta touto legei autois Lazaros ho philos hēmōn kekoimētai alla poreuomai hina exypnisō auton',
   '''Our friend'' (ho philos hēmōn — our beloved friend; philos, from phileō). ''Sleepeth'' (kekoimētai — has fallen asleep; perfect tense of koimaomai, to sleep). Jesus uses sleep as a euphemism for death — a usage common in both the OT (Daniel 12:2; Psalm 13:3) and the NT (1 Thessalonians 4:13-14; 1 Corinthians 15:51). For Jesus, death is merely sleep because he has the power to ''awake'' (exypnisō — rouse from sleep) the dead. The metaphor implies that death for the believer is temporary and reversible.',
   NULL),
  (12, 'Then said his disciples, Lord, if he sleep, he shall do well.',
   'εἶπον οὖν οἱ μαθηταὶ αὐτοῦ Κύριε εἰ κεκοίμηται σωθήσεται',
   'eipon oun hoi mathētai autou Kyrie ei kekoimētai sōthēsetai',
   '''If he sleep, he shall do well'' (ei kekoimētai sōthēsetai — if he has fallen asleep, he will be saved/recover). The disciples take Jesus literally: natural sleep in illness is a sign of recovery. ''Shall do well'' (sōthēsetai — will be saved, healed, restored; from sōzō). The misunderstanding is characteristic of Johannine irony: the disciples think the crisis is past, when in fact the greatest crisis — and the greatest miracle — lies ahead.',
   NULL),
  (13, 'Howbeit Jesus spake of his death: but they thought that he had spoken of taking of rest in sleep.',
   'εἰρήκει δὲ ὁ Ἰησοῦς περὶ τοῦ θανάτου αὐτοῦ ἐκεῖνοι δὲ ἔδοξαν ὅτι περὶ τῆς κοιμήσεως τοῦ ὕπνου λέγει',
   'eirēkei de ho Iēsous peri tou thanatou autou ekeinoi de edoxan hoti peri tēs koimēseōs tou hypnou legei',
   'John''s editorial clarification. ''Death'' (thanatos) versus ''rest in sleep'' (koimēsis tou hypnou — the repose of natural sleep). The disciples'' misunderstanding highlights the difference between human and divine perspective: they see illness; Jesus sees death. They hope for recovery; Jesus plans resurrection. This is the Johannine pattern of earthly versus heavenly understanding (cf. 3:3-4 with Nicodemus; 4:10-11 with the Samaritan woman).',
   NULL),
  (14, 'Then said Jesus unto them plainly, Lazarus is dead.',
   'τότε οὖν εἶπεν αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς παρρησίᾳ Λάζαρος ἀπέθανεν',
   'tote oun eipen autois ho Iēsous parrēsia Lazaros apethanen',
   '''Plainly'' (parrēsia — openly, with boldness, without metaphor). ''Lazarus is dead'' (Lazaros apethanen — Lazarus died; aorist tense: a definite past event). Jesus removes all ambiguity. The blunt declaration contrasts with the gentle euphemism of v.11. There is no sentimentality: Jesus states the fact because the fact is the foundation of the miracle. Death must be real before resurrection can be real. The verb apethanen (he died) is simple and final — and yet, for Jesus, it is not the last word.',
   NULL),
  (15, 'And I am glad for your sakes that I was not there, to the intent ye may believe; nevertheless let us go unto him.',
   'καὶ χαίρω δι᾽ ὑμᾶς ἵνα πιστεύσητε ὅτι οὐκ ἤμην ἐκεῖ ἀλλ᾽ ἄγωμεν πρὸς αὐτόν',
   'kai chairō di hymas hina pisteusēte hoti ouk ēmēn ekei all agōmen pros auton',
   '''I am glad'' (chairō — I rejoice). Jesus rejoices not in death but in the opportunity for faith: ''that ye may believe'' (hina pisteusēte — purpose clause: so that you might come to believe). Had Jesus been present, he would have healed Lazarus (as the sisters note, vv.21, 32), and the disciples would have witnessed a healing — impressive but not unprecedented. By allowing death, Jesus creates the occasion for resurrection, a far greater revelation of his glory and identity. ''Let us go unto him'' (agōmen pros auton — let us go to him) — Jesus goes to the dead man, just as the Good Shepherd goes to the sheep.',
   NULL),
  (16, 'Then said Thomas, which is called Didymus, unto his fellowdisciples, Let us also go, that we may die with him.',
   'εἶπεν οὖν Θωμᾶς ὁ λεγόμενος Δίδυμος τοῖς συμμαθηταῖς Ἄγωμεν καὶ ἡμεῖς ἵνα ἀποθάνωμεν μετ᾽ αὐτοῦ',
   'eipen oun Thōmas ho legomenos Didymos tois symmathētais Agōmen kai hēmeis hina apothanōmen met autou',
   '''Thomas, which is called Didymus'' (Thōmas... Didymos — both words mean ''twin,'' the first Aramaic, the second Greek). ''Let us also go, that we may die with him'' — a statement of courageous loyalty, not despair. Thomas expects death in Judaea (cf. v.8) but is willing to share it. This is the same Thomas who later doubts the resurrection (20:25) — John portrays him with psychological complexity. His loyalty is genuine even when his faith is incomplete. ''With him'' (met autou) probably refers to Jesus, not Lazarus.',
   NULL),
  (17, 'Then when Jesus came, he found that he had lain in the grave four days already.',
   'ἐλθὼν οὖν ὁ Ἰησοῦς εὗρεν αὐτὸν τέσσαρας ἤδη ἡμέρας ἔχοντα ἐν τῷ μνημείῳ',
   'elthōn oun ho Iēsous heuren auton tessaras ēdē hēmeras echonta en tō mnēmeiō',
   '''Four days already'' (tessaras ēdē hēmeras — four days already in the tomb). The chronology: one day for the message to reach Jesus, two days of delay (v.6), one day for the journey = four days. The four-day detail is crucial: by Jewish reckoning, after three days decomposition was advanced and the soul was considered permanently departed. Four days placed the death beyond any natural possibility of recovery. This is not a coma, not a premature burial — it is verified, irreversible death. Jesus meets death at its most definitive.',
   NULL),
  (18, 'Now Bethany was nigh unto Jerusalem, about fifteen furlongs off:',
   'ἦν δὲ ἡ Βηθανία ἐγγὺς τῶν Ἱεροσολύμων ὡς ἀπὸ σταδίων δεκαπέντε',
   'ēn de hē Bēthania engys tōn Hierosolymōn hōs apo stadiōn dekapente',
   '''Fifteen furlongs'' (stadiōn dekapente — about 15 stadia, roughly 1.7 miles or 2.8 km). John notes the proximity to Jerusalem to explain why many Jerusalem Jews have come to mourn (v.19) and why news of the miracle will quickly reach the Pharisees (v.46). The nearness also foreshadows Jesus'' final entry into Jerusalem (12:1, 12). Archaeological identification places Bethany at modern el-Azariyeh (''Place of Lazarus'') on the eastern slope of the Mount of Olives.',
   NULL),
  (19, 'And many of the Jews came to Martha and Mary, to comfort them concerning their brother.',
   'πολλοὶ δὲ ἐκ τῶν Ἰουδαίων ἐληλύθεισαν πρὸς τὴν Μάρθαν καὶ Μαριὰμ ἵνα παραμυθήσωνται αὐτὰς περὶ τοῦ ἀδελφοῦ',
   'polloi de ek tōn Ioudaiōn elēlytheisan pros tēn Marthan kai Mariam hina paramythēsōntai autas peri tou adelphou',
   '''Many of the Jews'' (polloi... ek tōn Ioudaiōn) — Jerusalem Jews who knew the family, likely of some social standing. ''To comfort'' (paramythēsōntai — to console, encourage alongside; from para + mythos). Jewish mourning customs included a seven-day period (shiv''ah) of intense grieving, during which neighbours and friends visited to comfort the bereaved. The visitors become eyewitnesses of the miracle (v.45) and potential witnesses in Jerusalem. Their presence serves God''s purpose in making the sign public.',
   NULL),
  (20, 'Then Martha, as soon as she heard that Jesus was coming, went and met him: but Mary sat still in the house.',
   'ἡ οὖν Μάρθα ὡς ἤκουσεν ὅτι Ἰησοῦς ἔρχεται ὑπήντησεν αὐτῷ Μαριὰμ δὲ ἐν τῷ οἴκῳ ἐκαθέζετο',
   'hē oun Martha hōs ēkousen hoti Iēsous erchetai hypēntēsen autō Mariam de en tō oikō ekathezeto',
   'Martha''s active response contrasts with Mary''s stillness — consistent with their characterisation in Luke 10:38-42. Martha is the doer, the initiator; Mary is the contemplative. ''Went and met him'' (hypēntēsen autō — went to meet him, went out to encounter him). ''Sat still in the house'' (en tō oikō ekathezeto — was sitting in the house), perhaps immobilised by grief, or receiving mourners. Both sisters will say the same words to Jesus (vv.21, 32), but their manner of approach differs.',
   NULL),
  (21, 'Then said Martha unto Jesus, Lord, if thou hadst been here, my brother had not died.',
   'εἶπεν οὖν ἡ Μάρθα πρὸς τὸν Ἰησοῦν Κύριε εἰ ἦς ὧδε οὐκ ἂν ἀπέθανεν ὁ ἀδελφός μου',
   'eipen oun hē Martha pros ton Iēsoun Kyrie ei ēs hōde ouk an apethanen ho adelphos mou',
   '''Lord, if thou hadst been here'' (Kyrie ei ēs hōde — Lord, if you had been here). This is a statement of faith, not reproach: Martha believes in Jesus'' power to heal. ''My brother had not died'' (ouk an apethanen ho adelphos mou — my brother would not have died; contrary-to-fact condition). Martha expresses what she knows: Jesus'' presence prevents death. What she does not yet know is that Jesus'' power extends beyond prevention to reversal — he can not only prevent death but conquer it.',
   NULL),
  (22, 'But I know, that even now, whatsoever thou wilt ask of God, God will give it thee.',
   'ἀλλὰ καὶ νῦν οἶδα ὅτι ὅσα ἂν αἰτήσῃ τὸν θεόν δώσει σοι ὁ θεός',
   'alla kai nyn oida hoti hosa an aitēsē ton theon dōsei soi ho theos',
   '''Even now'' (kai nyn — even at this point, even after death). Martha''s faith reaches beyond the moment: she believes Jesus can still do something, though she may not know exactly what. ''Whatsoever thou wilt ask of God'' (hosa an aitēsē ton theon — whatever you might ask God). Some interpret this as tentative hope for resurrection; others as a general confession of Jesus'' relationship with the Father. Jesus will correct her theology slightly: he does not ask the Father for resurrection power — he possesses it inherently as the Son (v.25).',
   NULL),
  (23, 'Jesus saith unto her, Thy brother shall rise again.',
   'λέγει αὐτῇ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ἀναστήσεται ὁ ἀδελφός σου',
   'legei autē ho Iēsous Anastēsetai ho adelphos sou',
   '''Shall rise again'' (anastēsetai — will rise up, will stand again; future middle of anistēmi). Jesus'' statement is deliberately ambiguous: it could mean the final resurrection (as Martha takes it, v.24) or an immediate raising. Jesus uses the ambiguity to draw out Martha''s theology and then transcend it. This is the Johannine pattern: begin with a statement the hearer interprets on one level, then elevate it to a higher plane (cf. 2:19-21; 3:3-5; 4:10-14).',
   NULL),
  (24, 'Martha saith unto him, I know that he shall rise again in the resurrection at the last day.',
   'λέγει αὐτῷ Μάρθα Οἶδα ὅτι ἀναστήσεται ἐν τῇ ἀναστάσει ἐν τῇ ἐσχάτῃ ἡμέρᾳ',
   'legei autō Martha Oida hoti anastēsetai en tē anastasei en tē eschatē hēmera',
   '''In the resurrection at the last day'' (en tē anastasei en tē eschatē hēmera — in the resurrection on the last day). Martha confesses the standard Pharisaic belief in future bodily resurrection (cf. Daniel 12:2; Acts 23:8). This is orthodox and correct — but it is comfort deferred. Martha knows the doctrine but needs the person. Jesus will now make the stunning claim that future resurrection is not merely a distant event but a present reality embodied in himself.',
   NULL),
  (25, 'Jesus said unto her, I am the resurrection, and the life: he that believeth in me, though he were dead, yet shall he live:',
   'εἶπεν αὐτῇ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ἐγώ εἰμι ἡ ἀνάστασις καὶ ἡ ζωή ὁ πιστεύων εἰς ἐμὲ κἂν ἀποθάνῃ ζήσεται',
   'eipen autē ho Iēsous Egō eimi hē anastasis kai hē zōē ho pisteuōn eis eme kan apothanē zēsetai',
   '''I am the resurrection, and the life'' (Egō eimi hē anastasis kai hē zōē) — the fifth ''I AM'' declaration in John (following 6:35; 8:12; 10:7, 11). Jesus does not say ''I perform resurrection'' or ''I will cause the resurrection'' but ''I AM the resurrection.'' Resurrection is not merely an event at the last day; it is a person standing before Martha. ''He that believeth in me, though he were dead, yet shall he live'' — physical death does not end the life of the believer because the source of life is the living Christ. This is the heart of Christian hope.',
   'THE RESURRECTION AND THE LIFE: This is one of the most important christological declarations in Scripture. (1) ''I AM'' (egō eimi) echoes the divine name (Exodus 3:14). (2) Jesus claims to BE resurrection, not merely to cause it — making resurrection a personal, relational reality. (3) ''Though he were dead, yet shall he live'' promises that physical death is not final for the believer. (4) The claim is immediately demonstrated in the raising of Lazarus (vv.43-44). (5) It will be ultimately vindicated in Jesus'' own resurrection (ch.20). This verse is the theological centre of John 11 and one of the great christological pillars of the NT.'),
  (26, 'And whosoever liveth and believeth in me shall never die. Believest thou this?',
   'καὶ πᾶς ὁ ζῶν καὶ πιστεύων εἰς ἐμὲ οὐ μὴ ἀποθάνῃ εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα πιστεύεις τοῦτο',
   'kai pas ho zōn kai pisteuōn eis eme ou mē apothanē eis ton aiōna pisteueis touto',
   '''Shall never die'' (ou mē apothanē eis ton aiōna — shall by no means die unto the age; double negative for emphatic denial). Two complementary promises: (1) v.25: even the physically dead believer will live; (2) v.26: the living believer will never truly die. Together they cover all cases: death cannot separate the believer from life in Christ. ''Believest thou this?'' (pisteueis touto — do you believe this?) — Jesus presses for personal faith, not mere doctrinal assent. The question is the pivot of the narrative: everything depends on the answer.',
   NULL),
  (27, 'She saith unto him, Yea, Lord: I believe that thou art the Christ, the Son of God, which should come into the world.',
   'λέγει αὐτῷ Ναί κύριε ἐγὼ πεπίστευκα ὅτι σὺ εἶ ὁ χριστός ὁ υἱὸς τοῦ θεοῦ ὁ εἰς τὸν κόσμον ἐρχόμενος',
   'legei autō Nai kyrie egō pepisteuка hoti sy ei ho christos ho huios tou theou ho eis ton kosmon erchomenos',
   '''Yea, Lord: I believe'' (Nai kyrie egō pepisteuка — Yes, Lord, I have believed and continue to believe; perfect tense indicating settled conviction). Martha''s confession is the Johannine equivalent of Peter''s confession (Matthew 16:16). Three titles: (1) ''the Christ'' (ho christos — the Messiah, the anointed one); (2) ''the Son of God'' (ho huios tou theou — not merely messianic title but divine relationship); (3) ''which should come into the world'' (ho eis ton kosmon erchomenos — the Coming One, cf. Malachi 3:1; Psalm 118:26). This is the model confession in John''s Gospel, the response the entire book aims to produce (20:31).',
   'Martha''s confession parallels and matches the stated purpose of John''s Gospel: ''that ye might believe that Jesus is the Christ, the Son of God; and that believing ye might have life through his name'' (20:31). Her faith is exemplary not because it is complete in understanding — she still protests at the tomb (v.39) — but because it rests on the right person.'),
  (28, 'And when she had so said, she went her way, and called Mary her sister secretly, saying, The Master is come, and calleth for thee.',
   'καὶ ταῦτα εἰποῦσα ἀπῆλθεν καὶ ἐφώνησεν Μαριὰμ τὴν ἀδελφὴν αὐτῆς λάθρᾳ εἰποῦσα Ὁ διδάσκαλος πάρεστιν καὶ φωνεῖ σε',
   'kai tauta eipousa apēlthen kai ephōnēsen Mariam tēn adelphēn autēs lathra eipousa Ho didaskalos parestin kai phōnei se',
   '''Secretly'' (lathra — in secret, privately) — Martha calls Mary quietly, perhaps to avoid alerting the mourners or the hostile authorities. ''The Master'' (ho didaskalos — the Teacher) — the title the sisters use for Jesus in private, suggesting an established relationship. ''Is come, and calleth for thee'' (parestin kai phōnei se — is present and is calling you) — Jesus actively summons Mary. The Good Shepherd calls his own by name (10:3).',
   NULL),
  (29, 'As soon as she heard that, she arose quickly, and came unto him.',
   'ἐκείνη ὡς ἤκουσεν ἠγέρθη ταχὺ καὶ ἤρχετο πρὸς αὐτόν',
   'ekeinē hōs ēkousen ēgerthē tachy kai ērcheto pros auton',
   '''Arose quickly'' (ēgerthē tachy — she rose up rapidly). Mary''s response is immediate and wholehearted. The verb ēgerthē (was raised/rose up, passive of egeirō) is the same root used for resurrection. ''Came unto him'' (ērcheto pros auton — was coming toward him; imperfect tense showing continuous action). Mary''s quick response to Jesus'' call mirrors the response of faith throughout John: when Jesus calls, those who know him come.',
   NULL),
  (30, 'Now Jesus was not yet come into the town, but was in that place where Martha met him.',
   'οὔπω δὲ ἐληλύθει ὁ Ἰησοῦς εἰς τὴν κώμην ἀλλ᾽ ἦν ἔτι ἐν τῷ τόπῳ ὅπου ὑπήντησεν αὐτῷ ἡ Μάρθα',
   'oupō de elēlythei ho Iēsous eis tēn kōmēn all ēn eti en tō topō hopou hypēntēsen autō hē Martha',
   'Jesus remains outside the village at the place where Martha met him. This geographical note explains why Mary must go out to him and why the mourners follow (v.31). It also ensures that the encounter with Mary and the scene at the tomb happen in sequence, each building the emotional and theological intensity of the narrative.',
   NULL),
  (31, 'The Jews then which were with her in the house, and comforted her, when they saw Mary, that she rose up hastily and went out, followed her, saying, She goeth unto the grave to weep there.',
   'οἱ οὖν Ἰουδαῖοι οἱ ὄντες μετ᾽ αὐτῆς ἐν τῇ οἰκίᾳ καὶ παραμυθούμενοι αὐτήν ἰδόντες τὴν Μαριὰμ ὅτι ταχέως ἀνέστη καὶ ἐξῆλθεν ἠκολούθησαν αὐτῇ εἰπόντες ὅτι Ὑπάγει εἰς τὸ μνημεῖον ἵνα κλαύσῃ ἐκεῖ',
   'hoi oun Ioudaioi hoi ontes met autēs en tē oikia kai paramythoumenoi autēn idontes tēn Mariam hoti tacheōs anestē kai exēlthen ēkolouthēsan autē eipontes hoti Hypagei eis to mnēmeion hina klausē ekei',
   'The mourners assume Mary is going to the tomb to weep (klausē — to weep loudly, wail). Their assumption is natural but wrong — she is going to Jesus. Their following her is providential: they become witnesses of the miracle. ''Rose up hastily'' (tacheōs anestē — quickly stood up) — the same haste noted in v.29. ''Followed her'' (ēkolouthēsan — they followed) uses the verb for discipleship (akoloutheō), though here the sense is physical following.',
   NULL),
  (32, 'Then when Mary was come where Jesus was, and saw him, she fell down at his feet, saying unto him, Lord, if thou hadst been here, my brother had not died.',
   'ἡ οὖν Μαριὰμ ὡς ἦλθεν ὅπου ἦν Ἰησοῦς ἰδοῦσα αὐτὸν ἔπεσεν αὐτοῦ πρὸς τοὺς πόδας λέγουσα αὐτῷ Κύριε εἰ ἦς ὧδε οὐκ ἂν μου ἀπέθανεν ὁ ἀδελφός',
   'hē oun Mariam hōs ēlthen hopou ēn Iēsous idousa auton epesen autou pros tous podas legousa autō Kyrie ei ēs hōde ouk an mou apethanen ho adelphos',
   'Mary says the same words as Martha (v.21), but her manner is different: she ''fell down at his feet'' (epesen autou pros tous podas — fell at his feet in worship/grief). Mary is consistently at Jesus'' feet in the Gospels (Luke 10:39; John 12:3). She does not add Martha''s ''even now'' expression of hope (v.22) — her grief is more overwhelming, less theological, more emotional. Yet the posture of falling at Jesus'' feet is itself an act of faith: she brings her grief to the right person.',
   NULL),
  (33, 'When Jesus therefore saw her weeping, and the Jews also weeping which came with her, he groaned in the spirit, and was troubled,',
   'Ἰησοῦς οὖν ὡς εἶδεν αὐτὴν κλαίουσαν καὶ τοὺς συνελθόντας αὐτῇ Ἰουδαίους κλαίοντας ἐνεβριμήσατο τῷ πνεύματι καὶ ἐτάραξεν ἑαυτόν',
   'Iēsous oun hōs eiden autēn klaiousan kai tous synelthontas autē Ioudaious klaiontas enebrimēsato tō pneumati kai etaraxen heauton',
   '''Groaned in the spirit'' (enebrimēsato tō pneumati — was deeply moved with indignation/emotion in his spirit). Embrimaomai is a strong word: it can mean to snort with anger (used of horses), to be indignant, to be deeply agitated. Some scholars suggest Jesus is angered by death itself — its unnaturalness, its destructive power over those he loves. Others suggest anger at the unbelief surrounding him. ''Was troubled'' (etaraxen heauton — he troubled himself; the active voice suggests Jesus allowed the emotion rather than being overwhelmed by it). The verse reveals the full humanity of Christ confronting the reality of death.',
   NULL),
  (34, 'And said, Where have ye laid him? They said unto him, Lord, come and see.',
   'καὶ εἶπεν Ποῦ τεθείκατε αὐτόν λέγουσιν αὐτῷ Κύριε ἔρχου καὶ ἴδε',
   'kai eipen Pou tetheikate auton legousin autō Kyrie erchou kai ide',
   '''Where have ye laid him?'' (Pou tetheikate auton — where have you placed him?). Jesus asks not because he does not know (cf. 2:25; 6:6) but because he enters fully into the human experience of loss. ''Come and see'' (erchou kai ide — come and see) — the same invitation used by Jesus to his first disciples (1:39, 46). Now the mourners invite Jesus to come and see death. He who said ''come and see life'' is invited to come and see a grave.',
   NULL),
  (35, 'Jesus wept.',
   'ἐδάκρυσεν ὁ Ἰησοῦς',
   'edakrysen ho Iēsous',
   'The shortest verse in the English Bible, but one of the most theologically significant. ''Wept'' (edakrysen — shed tears; aorist of dakryō, to weep silently, with tears). This is a different word from klaō (to wail loudly) used of Mary and the Jews. Jesus does not wail; he weeps quietly, with deep feeling. The incarnate God weeps at a human grave. This is not theatrical — it is genuine grief. Yet Jesus weeps knowing he is about to raise Lazarus. His tears reveal that even when resurrection is certain, the present pain of death is real and worthy of compassion. The verse refutes both Docetism (Jesus was truly human, truly feeling) and Stoicism (emotion is not weakness but an expression of love).',
   'JESUS WEPT — THE HUMANITY OF THE SON: This verse is the supreme NT demonstration that the incarnation involved genuine human emotion. Jesus weeps not from helplessness but from love. He has the power to raise Lazarus and he knows he will — yet he still weeps. His tears affirm that grief is not lack of faith and that compassion is a divine attribute. ''In all their affliction he was afflicted'' (Isaiah 63:9). ''We have not an high priest which cannot be touched with the feeling of our infirmities'' (Hebrews 4:15).'),
  (36, 'Then said the Jews, Behold how he loved him!',
   'ἔλεγον οὖν οἱ Ἰουδαῖοι Ἴδε πῶς ἐφίλει αὐτόν',
   'elegon oun hoi Ioudaioi Ide pōs ephilei auton',
   '''Behold how he loved him!'' (Ide pōs ephilei auton — See how he was loving him!). The Jews use phileō (personal, affectionate love) — they recognise genuine human friendship. Their observation is correct but incomplete: Jesus'' love extends far beyond what they can see. He loves Lazarus not only with human affection but with the eternal love of God, a love that will now express itself not merely in tears but in the conquest of death.',
   NULL),
  (37, 'And some of them said, Could not this man, which opened the eyes of the blind, have caused that even this man should not have died?',
   'τινὲς δὲ ἐξ αὐτῶν εἶπον Οὐκ ἐδύνατο οὗτος ὁ ἀνοίξας τοὺς ὀφθαλμοὺς τοῦ τυφλοῦ ποιῆσαι ἵνα καὶ οὗτος μὴ ἀποθάνῃ',
   'tines de ex autōn eipon Ouk edynato houtos ho anoixas tous ophthalmous tou typhlou poiēsai hina kai houtos mē apothanē',
   '''Could not this man?'' (Ouk edynato houtos — was not this man able?). They reference the healing of the blind man (ch.9), showing that miracle was widely known. Their question is posed negatively, implying doubt or criticism: if he could heal blindness, why not prevent death? The question is ironic: they wonder if Jesus could have prevented death, not imagining he can reverse it. They limit his power to prevention; Jesus will demonstrate power over death itself.',
   NULL),
  (38, 'Jesus therefore again groaning in himself cometh to the grave. It was a cave, and a stone lay upon it.',
   'Ἰησοῦς οὖν πάλιν ἐμβριμώμενος ἐν ἑαυτῷ ἔρχεται εἰς τὸ μνημεῖον ἦν δὲ σπήλαιον καὶ λίθος ἐπέκειτο ἐπ᾽ αὐτῷ',
   'Iēsous oun palin embrimōmenos en heautō erchetai eis to mnēmeion ēn de spēlaion kai lithos epekeito ep autō',
   '''Again groaning in himself'' (palin embrimōmenos en heautō — again deeply moved/indignant within himself). The repetition of embrimaomai (cf. v.33) underscores the intensity of Jesus'' emotion. ''A cave'' (spēlaion — a cave, grotto) — typical Jewish burial: a cave or rock-cut tomb, natural or hewn. ''A stone lay upon it'' (lithos epekeito ep autō — a stone was placed upon it). The stone sealed the tomb against animals and marked the finality of death. This stone must be removed before life can come forth — foreshadowing 20:1, where another stone is removed from another tomb.',
   NULL),
  (39, 'Jesus said, Take ye away the stone. Martha, the sister of him that was dead, saith unto him, Lord, by this time he stinketh: for he hath been dead four days.',
   'λέγει ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ἄρατε τὸν λίθον λέγει αὐτῷ ἡ ἀδελφὴ τοῦ τετελευτηκότος Μάρθα Κύριε ἤδη ὄζει τεταρταῖος γάρ ἐστιν',
   'legei ho Iēsous Arate ton lithon legei autō hē adelphē tou teteleutēkotos Martha Kyrie ēdē ozei tetartaios gar estin',
   '''Take ye away the stone'' (Arate ton lithon — lift up the stone). Jesus could have spoken through the stone, but he involves human action — a pattern throughout his ministry (fill the waterpots, John 2:7; cast the net, John 21:6). ''He stinketh'' (ēdē ozei — he already smells; present tense: the odour is already present). ''Four days'' (tetartaios — a fourth-day one). Martha''s protest reveals that her confession (v.27) has not yet fully grasped what Jesus is about to do. Faith in Jesus as the Christ does not automatically mean understanding every implication. Martha believes in who Jesus is but struggles with what he is about to do.',
   NULL),
  (40, 'Jesus saith unto her, Said I not unto thee, that, if thou wouldest believe, thou shouldest see the glory of God?',
   'λέγει αὐτῇ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Οὐκ εἶπόν σοι ὅτι ἐὰν πιστεύσῃς ὄψῃ τὴν δόξαν τοῦ θεοῦ',
   'legei autē ho Iēsous Ouk eipon soi hoti ean pisteusēs opsē tēn doxan tou theou',
   '''Said I not unto thee?'' (Ouk eipon soi — Did I not tell you?). Jesus recalls v.4 (''for the glory of God'') and vv.25-26 (''I am the resurrection''). ''If thou wouldest believe, thou shouldest see the glory of God'' (ean pisteusēs opsē tēn doxan tou theou — if you believe, you will see God''s glory). The order is significant: belief precedes sight. This is the opposite of the world''s demand to see before believing. Glory (doxa) will be manifested in the resurrection of Lazarus — a visible display of divine power that rewards faith and invites it.',
   NULL),
  (41, 'Then they took away the stone from the place where the dead was laid. And Jesus lifted up his eyes, and said, Father, I thank thee that thou hast heard me.',
   'ἦραν οὖν τὸν λίθον ὁ δὲ Ἰησοῦς ἦρεν τοὺς ὀφθαλμοὺς ἄνω καὶ εἶπεν Πάτερ εὐχαριστῶ σοι ὅτι ἤκουσάς μου',
   'ēran oun ton lithon ho de Iēsous ēren tous ophthalmous anō kai eipen Pater eucharistō soi hoti ēkousas mou',
   '''Lifted up his eyes'' (ēren tous ophthalmous anō — raised his eyes upward), the posture of prayer (cf. 17:1). ''Father, I thank thee'' (Pater eucharistō soi — Father, I give thanks to you). Jesus prays not to obtain power but to acknowledge the source of power and to demonstrate his relationship with the Father. ''That thou hast heard me'' (hoti ēkousas mou — that you heard me; aorist: already heard) — the answer is already given before the prayer is spoken publicly. Jesus'' prayer life with the Father is continuous (v.42).',
   NULL),
  (42, 'And I knew that thou hearest me always: but because of the people which stand by I said it, that they may believe that thou hast sent me.',
   'ἐγὼ δὲ ᾔδειν ὅτι πάντοτέ μου ἀκούεις ἀλλὰ διὰ τὸν ὄχλον τὸν περιεστῶτα εἶπον ἵνα πιστεύσωσιν ὅτι σύ με ἀπέστειλας',
   'egō de ēdein hoti pantote mou akoueis alla dia ton ochlon ton periestōta eipon hina pisteusōsin hoti sy me apesteilas',
   '''Thou hearest me always'' (pantote mou akoueis — you always hear me). Jesus enjoys unbroken communion with the Father — his prayer is never unheard. ''Because of the people which stand by'' (dia ton ochlon ton periestōta — for the sake of the crowd standing around). The public prayer is for the benefit of the witnesses, not for Jesus'' need. ''That they may believe that thou hast sent me'' (hina pisteusōsin hoti sy me apesteilas) — the purpose of the sign is faith in Jesus'' divine mission. Every miracle in John serves this evangelistic purpose (20:31).',
   NULL),
  (43, 'And when he thus had spoken, he cried with a loud voice, Lazarus, come forth.',
   'καὶ ταῦτα εἰπὼν φωνῇ μεγάλῃ ἐκραύγασεν Λάζαρε δεῦρο ἔξω',
   'kai tauta eipōn phōnē megalē ekraugasen Lazare deuro exō',
   '''Cried with a loud voice'' (phōnē megalē ekraugasen — shouted with a great voice). The loud cry is not necessity but authority: Jesus speaks as the sovereign Lord of life and death. ''Lazarus, come forth'' (Lazare deuro exō — Lazarus, come out here). The command is personal — Jesus calls Lazarus by name, as the Good Shepherd calls his sheep (10:3). Augustine noted: had Jesus not specified ''Lazarus,'' all the dead would have come forth. The voice that created the world (1:3) now commands the dead to live. ''The dead shall hear the voice of the Son of God: and they that hear shall live'' (5:25) is fulfilled before their eyes.',
   'THE VOICE OF THE SON OF GOD: This moment fulfils Jesus'' own prophecy in 5:25, 28-29: ''The hour is coming, and now is, when the dead shall hear the voice of the Son of God: and they that hear shall live.'' The raising of Lazarus is a preview of the general resurrection — the same voice, the same authority, the same power. What happens at this tomb will happen at every tomb on the last day. The personal summons (''Lazarus'') reflects the intimate, individual nature of resurrection: God knows each by name.'),
  (44, 'And he that was dead came forth, bound hand and foot with graveclothes: and his face was bound about with a napkin. Jesus saith unto them, Loose him, and let him go.',
   'ἐξῆλθεν ὁ τεθνηκὼς δεδεμένος τοὺς πόδας καὶ τὰς χεῖρας κειρίαις καὶ ἡ ὄψις αὐτοῦ σουδαρίῳ περιεδέδετο λέγει αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς Λύσατε αὐτὸν καὶ ἄφετε αὐτὸν ὑπάγειν',
   'exēlthen ho tethnēkōs dedemenos tous podas kai tas cheiras keiriais kai hē opsis autou soudariō periedeto legei autois ho Iēsous Lysate auton kai aphete auton hypagein',
   '''He that was dead'' (ho tethnēkōs — the one having died; perfect participle: the one who was and had been dead). ''Came forth'' (exēlthen — came out). ''Bound hand and foot with graveclothes'' (dedemenos tous podas kai tas cheiras keiriais — bound at feet and hands with linen strips). ''Face bound about with a napkin'' (soudariō periedeto — wrapped around with a burial cloth). Lazarus emerges still in his grave bindings — unlike Jesus at his resurrection, whose grave clothes will be found neatly folded (20:6-7). ''Loose him, and let him go'' (Lysate auton kai aphete auton hypagein — unbind him and let him go). Again Jesus involves human action. The spiritual application is clear: Christ gives life; the community removes the remnants of death.',
   NULL),
  (45, 'Then many of the Jews which came to Mary, and had seen the things which Jesus did, believed on him.',
   'πολλοὶ οὖν ἐκ τῶν Ἰουδαίων οἱ ἐλθόντες πρὸς τὴν Μαριὰμ καὶ θεασάμενοι ἃ ἐποίησεν ἐπίστευσαν εἰς αὐτόν',
   'polloi oun ek tōn Ioudaiōn hoi elthontes pros tēn Mariam kai theasamenoi ha epoiēsen episteusan eis auton',
   '''Many... believed on him'' (polloi... episteusan eis auton — many believed into him). The sign achieves its intended purpose: faith. ''Had seen the things which Jesus did'' (theasamenoi ha epoiēsen — having beheld what he did). The verb theaomai implies careful, attentive observation — not a casual glance but witnessing. Yet ''many'' is not ''all'' — some respond with faith, others with hostility (v.46). The same evidence produces opposite responses, a recurring Johannine theme.',
   NULL),
  (46, 'But some of them went their ways to the Pharisees, and told them what things Jesus had done.',
   'τινὲς δὲ ἐξ αὐτῶν ἀπῆλθον πρὸς τοὺς Φαρισαίους καὶ εἶπαν αὐτοῖς ἃ ἐποίησεν Ἰησοῦς',
   'tines de ex autōn apēlthon pros tous Pharisaious kai eipan autois ha epoiēsen Iēsous',
   '''Some of them went... to the Pharisees'' — not necessarily hostile witnesses; they may have been reporting in awe or seeking guidance. But the result is the same: the authorities are informed. ''Told them what things Jesus had done'' — they do not deny the miracle; they report it. The Pharisees'' problem is not lack of evidence but the theological and political implications of the evidence. John''s irony: the miracle that should have produced universal faith instead triggers the plot to kill Jesus.',
   NULL),
  (47, 'Then gathered the chief priests and the Pharisees a council, and said, What do we? for this man doeth many miracles.',
   'συνήγαγον οὖν οἱ ἀρχιερεῖς καὶ οἱ Φαρισαῖοι συνέδριον καὶ ἔλεγον Τί ποιοῦμεν ὅτι οὗτος ὁ ἄνθρωπος πολλὰ ποιεῖ σημεῖα',
   'synēgagon oun hoi archiereis kai hoi Pharisaioi synedrion kai elegon Ti poioumen hoti houtos ho anthrōpos polla poiei sēmeia',
   '''Gathered a council'' (synēgagon... synedrion — convened a Sanhedrin meeting; the supreme Jewish court). ''What do we?'' (Ti poioumen — what are we doing? What shall we do?). ''This man doeth many miracles'' (houtos ho anthrōpos polla poiei sēmeia — this man performs many signs). They do not deny the signs — they acknowledge them openly. Their concern is not theological (''is he the Messiah?'') but political (''what will happen to us?''). They refer to Jesus dismissively as ''this man'' (houtos ho anthrōpos). The supreme irony: religious leaders acknowledge undeniable signs and respond with a murder plot.',
   NULL),
  (48, 'If we let him thus alone, all men will believe on him: and the Romans shall come and take away both our place and nation.',
   'ἐὰν ἀφῶμεν αὐτὸν οὕτως πάντες πιστεύσουσιν εἰς αὐτόν καὶ ἐλεύσονται οἱ Ῥωμαῖοι καὶ ἀροῦσιν ἡμῶν καὶ τὸν τόπον καὶ τὸ ἔθνος',
   'ean aphōmen auton houtōs pantes pisteusousin eis auton kai eleusontai hoi Rhōmaioi kai arousin hēmōn kai ton topon kai to ethnos',
   '''All men will believe on him'' (pantes pisteusousin eis auton) — an exaggerated fear, yet ironically pointing to truth: Jesus will indeed draw all men to himself (12:32). ''The Romans shall come'' — they fear Roman reprisal against a messianic movement. ''Our place'' (ton topon — the Temple, their centre of power) ''and nation'' (to ethnos). The tragic irony: the very thing they sought to prevent by killing Jesus — Roman destruction of Temple and nation — happened in AD 70 precisely because they rejected him. Their political calculation proved catastrophically wrong.',
   NULL),
  (49, 'And one of them, named Caiaphas, being the high priest that same year, said unto them, Ye know nothing at all,',
   'εἷς δέ τις ἐξ αὐτῶν Καϊάφας ἀρχιερεὺς ὢν τοῦ ἐνιαυτοῦ ἐκείνου εἶπεν αὐτοῖς Ὑμεῖς οὐκ οἴδατε οὐδέν',
   'heis de tis ex autōn Kaiaphas archiereus ōn tou eniautou ekeinou eipen autois Hymeis ouk oidate ouden',
   '''Caiaphas'' (Kaiaphas — Joseph Caiaphas, son-in-law of Annas, served as high priest c. AD 18-36). ''Being the high priest that same year'' — John does not imply annual rotation of high priests (the office was for life); he emphasises that Caiaphas held office ''that year'' — the year of Jesus'' death, the most consequential year in history. ''Ye know nothing at all'' (Hymeis ouk oidate ouden — you know nothing whatsoever) — arrogant dismissal of his fellow council members, typical of political pragmatism.',
   NULL),
  (50, 'Nor consider that it is expedient for us, that one man should die for the people, and that the whole nation perish not.',
   'οὐδὲ λογίζεσθε ὅτι συμφέρει ὑμῖν ἵνα εἷς ἄνθρωπος ἀποθάνῃ ὑπὲρ τοῦ λαοῦ καὶ μὴ ὅλον τὸ ἔθνος ἀπόληται',
   'oude logizesthe hoti sympherei hymin hina heis anthrōpos apothanē hyper tou laou kai mē holon to ethnos apolētai',
   '''It is expedient'' (sympherei — it is profitable, advantageous, beneficial). ''One man should die for the people'' (heis anthrōpos apothanē hyper tou laou — one man die on behalf of the people). Caiaphas speaks as a cold political calculator: better one man dead than Roman intervention. But his words carry a meaning far deeper than he intends: Jesus will indeed die ''for the people'' — not as a political sacrifice but as the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world (1:29). The high priest unwittingly pronounces the theology of substitutionary atonement.',
   'UNWITTING PROPHECY OF SUBSTITUTIONARY ATONEMENT: Caiaphas'' words — ''one man should die for the people'' — express the core of atonement theology. The preposition hyper (on behalf of, in place of) is the language of substitution (cf. Mark 10:45; 2 Corinthians 5:21; Galatians 3:13; 1 Peter 3:18). Caiaphas means political expediency; God means redemptive substitution. The high priest, whose office was to offer sacrifice for sin, unknowingly announces the ultimate sacrifice.'),
  (51, 'And this spake he not of himself: but being high priest that year, he prophesied that Jesus should die for that nation;',
   'τοῦτο δὲ ἀφ᾽ ἑαυτοῦ οὐκ εἶπεν ἀλλὰ ἀρχιερεὺς ὢν τοῦ ἐνιαυτοῦ ἐκείνου ἐπροφήτευσεν ὅτι ἔμελλεν Ἰησοῦς ἀποθνῄσκειν ὑπὲρ τοῦ ἔθνους',
   'touto de aph heautou ouk eipen alla archiereus ōn tou eniautou ekeinou eprophēteusen hoti emellen Iēsous apothnēskein hyper tou ethnous',
   '''Not of himself'' (aph heautou ouk eipen — he did not speak from himself). ''He prophesied'' (eprophēteusen — he prophesied, spoke by divine inspiration). John makes an extraordinary claim: even the wicked high priest, acting in his official capacity, could be the instrument of divine prophecy. This is consistent with OT precedent (Balaam, Numbers 22-24; Saul, 1 Samuel 19:23-24). God''s sovereignty overrules human intention: Caiaphas means murder; God means salvation. The office speaks truth even when the officeholder acts in malice.',
   NULL),
  (52, 'And not for that nation only, but that also he should gather together in one the children of God that were scattered abroad.',
   'καὶ οὐχ ὑπὲρ τοῦ ἔθνους μόνον ἀλλ᾽ ἵνα καὶ τὰ τέκνα τοῦ θεοῦ τὰ διεσκορπισμένα συναγάγῃ εἰς ἕν',
   'kai ouch hyper tou ethnous monon all hina kai ta tekna tou theou ta dieskorpismena synagagē eis hen',
   '''Not for that nation only'' — John expands the scope of Jesus'' death beyond Israel. ''The children of God that were scattered abroad'' (ta tekna tou theou ta dieskorpismena — the scattered children of God). This refers to Gentile believers who will be gathered into one people of God through the cross (cf. 10:16: ''other sheep I have, which are not of this fold... one flock, one shepherd''). ''Gather together in one'' (synagagē eis hen — gather into unity) — the cross is the instrument of universal reconciliation (Ephesians 2:14-16). Jesus'' death is not a national tragedy but a cosmic redemption.',
   NULL),
  (53, 'Then from that day forth they took counsel together for to put him to death.',
   'ἀπ᾽ ἐκείνης οὖν τῆς ἡμέρας ἐβουλεύσαντο ἵνα ἀποκτείνωσιν αὐτόν',
   'ap ekeinēs oun tēs hēmeras ebouleusanto hina apokteinōsin auton',
   '''From that day forth'' (ap ekeinēs tēs hēmeras — from that day). ''They took counsel together to put him to death'' (ebouleusanto hina apokteinōsin auton — they deliberated in order to kill him). The decision is now formal and corporate — the Sanhedrin has resolved to execute Jesus. The supreme irony of John 11: the one who raised the dead is condemned to death because he raised the dead. The miracle that most clearly demonstrated Jesus'' divine authority becomes the immediate cause of his crucifixion. Life conquers death, and death responds by plotting against life.',
   NULL),
  (54, 'Jesus therefore walked no more openly among the Jews; but went thence unto a country near to the wilderness, into a city called Ephraim, and there continued with his disciples.',
   'ὁ οὖν Ἰησοῦς οὐκέτι παρρησίᾳ περιεπάτει ἐν τοῖς Ἰουδαίοις ἀλλὰ ἀπῆλθεν ἐκεῖθεν εἰς τὴν χώραν ἐγγὺς τῆς ἐρήμου εἰς Ἐφραὶμ λεγομένην πόλιν κἀκεῖ ἔμεινεν μετὰ τῶν μαθητῶν',
   'ho oun Iēsous ouketi parrēsia periepatei en tois Ioudaiois alla apēlthen ekeithen eis tēn chōran engys tēs erēmou eis Ephraim legomenēn polin kakei emeinen meta tōn mathētōn',
   '''No more openly'' (ouketi parrēsia — no longer with openness/boldness). Jesus'' withdrawal is not fear but timing: his ''hour'' is near but has not yet come. ''Ephraim'' (Ephraim — likely modern et-Taiyibeh, about 15 miles northeast of Jerusalem, near the wilderness). ''Continued with his disciples'' (emeinen meta tōn mathētōn — he remained with his disciples). This quiet retreat before the Passover is a period of preparation, like the calm before the storm. The next time Jesus comes to Jerusalem, it will be for the triumphal entry and the cross.',
   NULL),
  (55, 'And the Jews'' passover was nigh at hand: and many went out of the country up to Jerusalem before the passover, to purify themselves.',
   'ἦν δὲ ἐγγὺς τὸ πάσχα τῶν Ἰουδαίων καὶ ἀνέβησαν πολλοὶ εἰς Ἱεροσόλυμα ἐκ τῆς χώρας πρὸ τοῦ πάσχα ἵνα ἁγνίσωσιν ἑαυτούς',
   'ēn de engys to pascha tōn Ioudaiōn kai anebēsan polloi eis Hierosolyma ek tēs chōras pro tou pascha hina hagnisōsin heautous',
   '''The Jews'' Passover'' — this is the third Passover mentioned in John (2:13; 6:4; 11:55), the one at which Jesus will die. ''To purify themselves'' (hagnisōsin heautous — to purify themselves ceremonially). Ritual purification was required before Passover participation (cf. Numbers 9:6-10; 2 Chronicles 30:17-18). Many arrived early to complete the process. The irony: while pilgrims purify themselves for Passover, the true Paschal Lamb is preparing for slaughter.',
   NULL),
  (56, 'Then sought they for Jesus, and spake among themselves, as they stood in the temple, What think ye, that he will not come to the feast?',
   'ἐζήτουν οὖν τὸν Ἰησοῦν καὶ ἔλεγον μετ᾽ ἀλλήλων ἐν τῷ ἱερῷ ἑστηκότες Τί δοκεῖ ὑμῖν ὅτι οὐ μὴ ἔλθῃ εἰς τὴν ἑορτήν',
   'ezētoun oun ton Iēsoun kai elegon met allēlōn en tō hierō hestēkotes Ti dokei hymin hoti ou mē elthē eis tēn heortēn',
   '''Sought they for Jesus'' (ezētoun ton Iēsoun — they were seeking Jesus). The crowds look for Jesus in the Temple courts with a mixture of curiosity and expectation. ''What think ye?'' (Ti dokei hymin — what does it seem to you?) — the question circulates through the crowd. ''That he will not come to the feast?'' — they suspect he will avoid the danger. But Jesus will come — the Lamb must be at the Passover. Their speculation creates dramatic tension: the reader knows Jesus will come, and what will happen when he does.',
   NULL),
  (57, 'Now both the chief priests and the Pharisees had given a commandment, that, if any man knew where he were, he should shew it, that they might take him.',
   'δεδώκεισαν δὲ οἱ ἀρχιερεῖς καὶ οἱ Φαρισαῖοι ἐντολὰς ἵνα ἐάν τις γνῷ ποῦ ἐστιν μηνύσῃ ὅπως πιάσωσιν αὐτόν',
   'dedōkeisan de hoi archiereis kai hoi Pharisaioi entolas hina ean tis gnō pou estin mēnysē hopōs piasōsin auton',
   '''Had given a commandment'' (dedōkeisan... entolas — had given orders; pluperfect: the orders were already in effect). ''If any man knew where he were, he should shew it'' — an informant directive, effectively making Jesus a wanted man. ''That they might take him'' (hopōs piasōsin auton — so that they might arrest him). The chapter ends with Jesus as a fugitive — the giver of life is hunted by those who deal in death. The net is closing. The next chapter opens with Jesus returning to Bethany (12:1), setting the final sequence in motion.',
   NULL)
) AS v(verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
WHERE b.name = 'John' AND c.chapter_number = 11;

-- Step 3: Insert word studies
INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, greek_word, transliteration, strongs_number, definition, word_order)
SELECT v.id, ws.greek_word, ws.transliteration, ws.strongs_number, ws.definition, ws.word_order
FROM verses v
JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  ('ἀνάστασις', 'anastasis', 'G386',
   'Resurrection, rising up, standing up again; the raising of the dead to life.',
   'From ana (up, again) + histēmi (to stand). In v.25, Jesus declares ''I am the resurrection'' (Egō eimi hē anastasis). Martha uses the word in v.24: ''I know that he shall rise again in the resurrection at the last day.'' Martha''s understanding is correct but incomplete — she knows anastasis as a future event. Jesus transforms the concept: resurrection is not merely an event but a person. ''I AM the resurrection'' means that wherever Jesus is, resurrection is present. The raising of Lazarus (v.44) is the visible proof of this claim. Anastasis occurs 42 times in the NT, with its theological weight concentrated in John 11, 1 Corinthians 15, and Romans 6.',
   1),
  ('ζωή', 'zōē', 'G2222',
   'Life, the vital principle of animate existence; in John, the divine, eternal life that comes from God.',
   'In v.25, ''I am the resurrection, and the life'' (kai hē zōē). Zōē in John is not merely biological existence (bios) but the quality of divine life that belongs to God and is communicated through the Son (1:4: ''In him was life''). This life is eternal in nature (3:16; 5:24; 6:47), present in possession (''hath everlasting life,'' 5:24), and indestructible by death (''shall never die,'' v.26). Jesus does not merely give life — he IS life. Zōē occurs 36 times in John, more than any other NT book.',
   2),
  ('κλαίω', 'klaiō', 'G2799',
   'To weep loudly, to wail, to cry with audible lamentation; to mourn with tears.',
   'Used of Mary (v.33: klaiousan — weeping), the Jews (v.33: klaiontas — weeping), and in the mourners'' assumption about Mary (v.31: klausē — to weep). Klaiō denotes loud, demonstrative grief — the wailing that was characteristic of Jewish mourning. In contrast, Jesus'' weeping in v.35 uses dakryō (to shed tears silently). The distinction is important: the mourners wail; Jesus weeps with quiet, deep emotion. Klaiō appears in Luke 19:41 of Jesus weeping over Jerusalem, but John reserves the stronger verb for the crowds and the quieter one for Jesus.',
   3),
  ('δακρύω', 'dakryō', 'G1145',
   'To shed tears, to weep silently; to cry without loud lamentation.',
   'Used only once in the NT, in v.35: ''Jesus wept'' (edakrysen ho Iēsous). Dakryō describes the quiet shedding of tears, distinct from klaiō (loud wailing). The word appears in classical Greek for tears of deep but controlled emotion. That John chooses this unique verb for Jesus'' weeping reveals the character of divine compassion: not theatrical display but genuine, restrained grief. The related noun dakryon (tear) appears in Hebrews 5:7 (Jesus offered prayers ''with strong crying and tears'') and Revelation 21:4 (''God shall wipe away all tears'').',
   4),
  ('ἐμβριμάομαι', 'embrimaomai', 'G1690',
   'To be deeply moved, to groan with indignation, to be sternly moved; originally: to snort (of horses).',
   'Used twice in this chapter: v.33 (enebrimēsato tō pneumati — he groaned in the spirit) and v.38 (embrimōmenos en heautō — groaning in himself). The word carries overtones of anger and indignation, not merely sadness. In Mark 1:43 and 14:5, it denotes stern warning; in Matthew 9:30, strong emotion. Jesus'' embrimaomai at the tomb suggests righteous anger at death itself — the invasion of God''s good creation by the enemy that sin has introduced. He is not merely sad; he is indignant at the destruction death causes.',
   5),
  ('σημεῖον', 'sēmeion', 'G4592',
   'Sign, miracle, wonder; an attesting act that points beyond itself to a deeper reality.',
   'In v.47, the Sanhedrin acknowledges ''this man doeth many signs'' (polla poiei sēmeia). In John, sēmeion is the preferred term for Jesus'' miracles (2:11, 23; 4:54; 6:2, 14, 26; 9:16; 12:18, 37; 20:30). A sēmeion is not merely a display of power but a revelatory act: it signifies something about Jesus'' identity and mission. The raising of Lazarus is the supreme sēmeion — it signifies Jesus as the resurrection and the life. Yet signs can be seen without being understood: the Sanhedrin acknowledges the signs and rejects their meaning.',
   6),
  ('συμφέρω', 'sympherō', 'G4851',
   'To be advantageous, profitable, expedient; to bring together for benefit.',
   'In v.50, Caiaphas says ''it is expedient for us'' (sympherei hymin — it is profitable for you). Sympherō means to bring together what is beneficial, to calculate advantage. Caiaphas uses it as cold political calculus: one death is cheaper than national catastrophe. But John sees deeper meaning: the ''expedience'' is divine, not political. It truly is ''expedient'' — not for the nation''s political survival but for the world''s salvation — that one man should die for the people. God''s expedience is redemption; Caiaphas'' expedience is expediency. The same word carries opposite meanings at human and divine levels.',
   7),
  ('κοιμάομαι', 'koimaomai', 'G2837',
   'To sleep, to fall asleep; euphemistically: to die, to be in the state of death.',
   'In v.11, ''Our friend Lazarus sleepeth'' (Lazaros ho philos hēmōn kekoimētai — Lazarus our friend has fallen asleep). Koimaomai is the standard NT euphemism for death (1 Corinthians 15:6, 18, 20, 51; 1 Thessalonians 4:13-15; Acts 7:60; 2 Peter 3:4). The metaphor of sleep for death is profoundly theological: sleep implies waking. The one who sleeps will rise. For Jesus, death is ''sleep'' because he has absolute power to ''awaken'' the dead (v.11: exypnisō — rouse from sleep). The English word ''cemetery'' derives from koimētērion (sleeping place), reflecting the Christian hope of resurrection.',
   8)
) AS ws(greek_word, transliteration, strongs_number, definition, word_order)
CROSS JOIN LATERAL (
  SELECT v2.id FROM verses v2
  JOIN chapters c2 ON v2.chapter_id = c2.id
  JOIN books b2 ON c2.book_id = b2.id
  WHERE b2.name = 'John' AND c2.chapter_number = 11
  AND v2.verse_number = CASE ws.word_order
    WHEN 1 THEN 25
    WHEN 2 THEN 25
    WHEN 3 THEN 33
    WHEN 4 THEN 35
    WHEN 5 THEN 33
    WHEN 6 THEN 47
    WHEN 7 THEN 50
    WHEN 8 THEN 11
  END
  LIMIT 1
) v
WHERE b.name = 'John' AND c.chapter_number = 11;

-- Step 4: Insert cross-references
INSERT INTO cross_references (verse_id, referenced_verse, relationship_type, note)
SELECT v.id, cr.referenced_verse, cr.relationship_type, cr.note
FROM verses v
JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1, 'Luke 10:38-42', 'parallel', 'Martha and Mary of Bethany, the sisters who hosted Jesus'),
  (1, 'John 12:1-3', 'forward', 'Lazarus at the supper where Mary anoints Jesus'' feet'),
  (3, 'John 11:36', 'thematic', '''He whom thou lovest'' — the Jews confirm Jesus'' love for Lazarus'),
  (4, 'John 9:3', 'thematic', '''That the works of God should be made manifest'' — suffering serves God''s glory'),
  (4, 'John 2:11', 'thematic', 'Jesus'' signs manifest his glory — Cana, the first sign'),
  (5, 'John 13:1', 'thematic', '''Having loved his own... he loved them unto the end'''),
  (6, 'John 2:4', 'thematic', '''Mine hour is not yet come'' — Jesus acts on divine timing, not human urgency'),
  (7, 'John 10:39-40', 'context', 'Jesus had withdrawn beyond Jordan after the Jews sought to stone him'),
  (8, 'John 10:31', 'context', '''The Jews took up stones again to stone him'' — the recent threat'),
  (9, 'John 8:12', 'thematic', '''I am the light of the world'' — walking in the day/light'),
  (9, 'John 12:35-36', 'forward', '''Walk while ye have the light'' — the same day/night metaphor'),
  (11, 'Daniel 12:2', 'allusion', '''Many of them that sleep in the dust of the earth shall awake'' — sleep as death'),
  (11, '1 Thessalonians 4:13-14', 'thematic', '''Them which are asleep'' — NT use of sleep for death in Christ'),
  (14, 'John 4:48', 'thematic', 'Jesus'' direct speech about signs and belief'),
  (15, 'John 20:31', 'thematic', '''That ye might believe'' — the purpose of signs in John'),
  (16, 'John 20:24-28', 'forward', 'Thomas who doubted the resurrection, then confessed ''My Lord and my God'''),
  (17, 'John 11:39', 'internal', '''Four days'' — confirmed by Martha at the tomb'),
  (21, 'John 11:32', 'internal', 'Mary says the same words: ''If thou hadst been here, my brother had not died'''),
  (23, 'Daniel 12:2', 'allusion', 'OT promise of bodily resurrection at the last day'),
  (24, 'Acts 23:6-8', 'thematic', 'Pharisaic belief in the resurrection of the dead'),
  (25, 'John 5:25-29', 'thematic', '''The dead shall hear the voice of the Son of God: and they that hear shall live'''),
  (25, 'John 14:6', 'thematic', '''I am the way, the truth, and the life'' — another I AM declaration'),
  (25, 'John 6:35', 'thematic', '''I am the bread of life'' — I AM parallel'),
  (25, 'Exodus 3:14', 'allusion', '''I AM THAT I AM'' — the divine name behind egō eimi'),
  (26, 'John 5:24', 'thematic', '''Is passed from death unto life'' — believers possess eternal life now'),
  (26, 'John 10:28', 'thematic', '''They shall never perish'' — eternal security of believers'),
  (27, 'Matthew 16:16', 'parallel', 'Peter''s confession: ''Thou art the Christ, the Son of the living God'''),
  (27, 'John 20:31', 'thematic', 'The confession John''s Gospel aims to produce in every reader'),
  (33, 'Hebrews 4:15', 'thematic', '''Touched with the feeling of our infirmities'' — Christ''s sympathy'),
  (33, 'Isaiah 63:9', 'allusion', '''In all their affliction he was afflicted'' — divine compassion'),
  (35, 'Luke 19:41', 'parallel', 'Jesus wept over Jerusalem — the other occasion of Jesus'' tears'),
  (35, 'Hebrews 5:7', 'thematic', '''With strong crying and tears'' — Jesus'' human experience of suffering'),
  (39, 'John 2:7', 'thematic', 'Jesus involves human action: ''Fill the waterpots'' / ''Take ye away the stone'''),
  (40, 'John 2:11', 'thematic', '''Manifested forth his glory'' — signs reveal divine glory'),
  (43, 'John 5:25', 'fulfilment', '''The dead shall hear the voice of the Son of God'' — fulfilled at Lazarus'' tomb'),
  (43, 'John 10:3', 'thematic', '''He calleth his own sheep by name'' — Lazarus called by name'),
  (44, 'John 20:6-7', 'contrast', 'At Jesus'' resurrection, the grave clothes were left behind, neatly folded'),
  (44, 'Revelation 1:18', 'thematic', '''I am he that liveth, and was dead; and, behold, I am alive for evermore'''),
  (48, 'John 12:19', 'forward', '''The world is gone after him'' — the Pharisees'' fear partially realised'),
  (50, 'Mark 10:45', 'thematic', '''The Son of man came to give his life a ransom for many'' — substitutionary atonement'),
  (50, '2 Corinthians 5:21', 'thematic', '''He hath made him to be sin for us'' — one dies for the people'),
  (50, '1 Peter 3:18', 'thematic', '''Christ also hath once suffered for sins, the just for the unjust'''),
  (51, 'Numbers 24:17', 'allusion', 'Balaam''s unwitting prophecy: even hostile agents speak God''s word'),
  (52, 'John 10:16', 'thematic', '''Other sheep I have, which are not of this fold'' — Gentile inclusion'),
  (52, 'Ephesians 2:14-16', 'thematic', 'Breaking the middle wall of partition — Jew and Gentile gathered into one'),
  (53, 'John 5:18', 'thematic', '''The Jews sought the more to kill him'' — escalating hostility'),
  (55, 'John 2:13', 'context', 'First Passover in John; this is the third — the Passover of the crucifixion'),
  (55, 'John 6:4', 'context', 'Second Passover in John — the Bread of Life discourse'),
  (55, '1 Corinthians 5:7', 'thematic', '''Christ our passover is sacrificed for us'' — Jesus as the true Paschal Lamb'),
  (57, 'John 7:30', 'thematic', '''No man laid hands on him, because his hour was not yet come'' — but the hour draws near')
) AS cr(verse_number, referenced_verse, relationship_type, note)
CROSS JOIN LATERAL (
  SELECT v2.id FROM verses v2
  JOIN chapters c2 ON v2.chapter_id = c2.id
  JOIN books b2 ON c2.book_id = b2.id
  WHERE b2.name = 'John' AND c2.chapter_number = 11 AND v2.verse_number = cr.verse_number
  LIMIT 1
) v
WHERE b.name = 'John' AND c.chapter_number = 11;
